editorialSummary.text: Celeb chef Gastón Acurio serves Peruvian seafood in a large, partially outdoor space on the pier.

text.text: The food here is excellent and has really flavorful options even for those with dietary restrictions. Very refreshing cocktails - definitely can’t skip one here as they are all so delicious! Service can be a bit lacking during weekend peak hours… make sure you get your entire order in at once as it’s hard to get their attention. The space is huge with lot of seating, and the outdoor seating has beautiful views of the bay so definitely make reservations in advance if you’d like the best tables!

text.text: La Mar truly exceeded all expectations! The food was not only incredibly fresh but also bursting with authentic Peruvian flavors. The ambiance added an extra layer of coziness to our dining experience, making it truly memorable. A big shoutout to Josh, our amazing waiter, for making our friend's birthday celebration extra special with a surprise cake and Polaroid picture. If you're in San Francisco and craving Peruvian cuisine, La Mar is an absolute must-visit!

editorialSummary.text: Contemporary waterside seafood eatery serving local oysters and clams, plus craft cocktails.

text.text: The service was great and super friendly. Clam chowder is awesome. Nice place to sit outside near the pier and have some oysters and drinks. The squid salad was a little bland, I think if they included more olives in it the saltiness would go a long way. Not enough of an issue for me to give less than 6 stars.

text.text:
I popped into this restaurant on a weekday and snagged a table right away. While parking in the area can be pricey ($8/hour!), a quick 7-8 minute walk northeast leads to free street parking and gives you a chance to explore the neighborhood.

The food was fantastic! I started with the Hog Island oysters, which were incredibly fresh and bursting with flavor, without a hint of fishiness. Next, I tried the garlic grilled oysters, cooked to perfection - juicy, creamy, and infused with garlicky goodness. The old bay fries were another highlight - crispy on the outside, fluffy on the inside, and seasoned with a hint of sweetness. Even the ketchup impressed me - tangy and refreshing, it complemented the fries perfectly.

The clam chowder wasn't your typical version. Instead of small bits, it showcased plump whole clams in a slightly thinner, yet still creamy broth that avoided being overly milky.

The service was friendly and attentive, ensuring a smooth and enjoyable dining experience. Plus, considering the high quality of the food, the prices were very reasonable. This hidden gem, even amidst the tourist crowds, offers excellent value and deserves a visit!

text.text:
Food was flavorful, but service was not that good.

Drinks took FOREVER to come! Had to wait at least 20-30 minutes is to get the drinks and honestly the restaurant was not even that full.
The servers also did not know who had ordered what drink, and we had to point them out after they call out each item.

They also messed up the order a bit. We asked for the special Barcha Hummus, but they got us all Classic Hummus orders instead.

Portion size was also very small for the price of the food. Appetizers came with 4 pieces each, and even entrees (especially salad) was very small.

Shrimp Skewers were lovely. Nice flavor with a good spice to it!

Zaatar flatbread was delicious - soft and warm and perfect hunt if za'atar.

Arugula Salad (with shrimp, dressing on the side) - nice combination of ingredients, but the volume was very small. Shrimp were nice and crispy, but quite oily.

People enjoyed the Beef Dumplings and Chicken & Specked Ham Croquettas.

Falafel wrap and Chicken Shawarma wrap were also a hit. Lots of fries on the side for those, and good size wrap too.

Chicken shawarma plate with rice seemed to have very little quantity of chicken too.
It was not supremely flavorful but just the right amount of flavor from that rice and chicken together.

Hummus was good, but we really wanted that special Barcha Hummus so kinda sad there.

text.text:
My taste buds have never experienced such a gastronomic delight as they did at Barcha Mediterranean Restaurant! From the moment we arrived, we were welcomed with open arms. Every dish that was served brought us closer to food heaven, making every second we spent there an unforgettable experience.

To kick off our culinary journey, we indulged in the mouth-watering Moroccan Cigars - a flavor explosion of lamb, mushrooms, gruyère, and cinnamon, paired with a tantalizing tamarind-mint chutney. And let's not forget the Barcha Spreads - a magnificent medley of baba ghanoush, labneh, muhammara, hummus, and bazlama that danced on our tongues.

For our main courses, the Persian Tahdig was the true star of the show, with its crispy saffron rice, duck leg, onions, barberries, fried egg, harissa yogurt, and herbs. The combination of crispy rice, juicy duck, and crispy onions was a symphony of flavors that left us weak in the knees. And the lamb shank leg with couscous was an absolute knockout, with tender meat that simply melted in our mouths.

As if that wasn't enough, we were served the divine Affogato - vanilla soft serve, and espresso, were delicious, and the Chocolate Cake was a sweet ending that left us wanting more.

Although the lighting kept adjusting during our time there dim to bright and keep going from our stayed from 6 pm - to 8 pm, it was hard on our eyes.

All in all, Barcha Mediterranean Restaurant offers more than just a meal - it is a journey through the Mediterranean region's culinary delights. Every dish served was a masterpiece, and the warm welcome made us feel like we were part of the family.

I was able to experience the restaurant but I won’t be coming back.

text.text:
The outlet in San Francisco is small, with limited seating area. I would advice to book a reservation before coming here as it can get crowded during the weekends and during holiday season.

Overall, the food and the ambience was good. They're known for different varieties of dimsums in vegetarian and non vegetarian options and also serve alcoholic and non alcoholic beverages. Their staff has carts which have different varieties of dimsums to choose from. Must try their sesame balls for dessert, it was delicious and not too sweet.

editorialSummary.text: Chinese restaurant in the Rincon Center presenting dim sum in a warm, well appointed dining room.

text.text:
Yank Sink offers a nice variety of dim sum, both steamed and fried, that's sure to please dim sum enthusiasts. Conveniently located inside the mall, its dining area extends into the mall itself, creating a casual and relaxed atmosphere.

The service at Yank Sink is efficient, with dim sum carts making rounds for patrons to choose from. Additionally, they offer the option to order some items via QR code, adding a modern touch to the dining experience.

One of the best parts about Yank Sink is its reasonable prices. For just $70, two people can enjoy a satisfying meal without breaking the bank.

In summary, Yank Sink is a solid choice for dim sum lovers looking for a tasty and affordable dining experience in a relaxed setting.

We’ve never had our food served in less than 60 seconds until we found this place. We also tried the Egg Custard Tart (but forgot to take a picture because it was so damn good) and it was delicious. Not too sweet, and the tart pastry was perfect. This is such an underrated restaurant and I must say this is my new favorite Dim Sum spot.

text.text: Excellent steakhouse in a chic, modern, stylish and fun venue. The atmosphere is everything and vibe is great. The colorful lights really add to the ambience. The food is second to none, so you will have to try it. The service is great but they are still not thinking in their customers shoe and sometimes recommend lots of stuff that are good, but not really necessary. And they will charge for all those recommendations. They are not very fast. So if you are in a rush, this cool place might not be right for the occasion. And the do have a happy hour menu which offers a pretty good deal.

text.text: I came for dinner with three others and was very impressed. A lot of things ordered were for the table to share, starting off with the mini wagyu burgers, truffle fries and the jalapeno pickled shrimp cocktail. Everything was delicious, the burgers were cooked to perfection, the fries were indeed truffle served with a great sauce and the jalapeno pickled shrimp cocktail was outstanding. For dinner we all ordered our own entrees but the sides were for the table to share, with entrees we ordered crispy brussel sprouts and lobster mac n cheese. The sides were fabulous and large enough to share between the four of us. I had the surf and turf for my entree which consist of a 6 oz filet and a lobster tail. The steak was perfectly cooked with the truffle butter on top and then they torch it in front of you, the lobster legitimately fell apart in your mouth it was so good. We had quite a few cocktails and a glass of wine, the strawberry cobbler cocktail was the highlight. The service was excellent, the food was a 10/10. The music is a bit weird/loud and the decor/horns on the wall are kinda weird BUT the food and service and the rest of the decor was amazing! We can’t wait to come back.

text.text: I decided to eat on a whim at Bar Sprezzatura  and did not know what to expect. I was drawn to the restaurant’s elegant art deco interior and was quickly impressed by the restaurant lively ambiance, delicious food and warm service. I started out with the outstanding osso buco ravioli special (it should be a permanent offering on the menu) and decided to try another pasta to see what the chef could do. The Ricotta e Mortadella Agnolotti did not disappoint. Both pastas were original creations that I have never eaten elsewhere. The service was attentive and friendly, and poured me a digestif at the end of the meal.

text.text:
I was blown away with how beautiful this space is! The colors, decor, and bar are breathtaking. It’s in the middle of the Embarcadero and kind of obscure to get to, but it makes it feel like a tucked-away secret.

The drinks are all $18+ which is what I guess the going rate is for beautiful ambiance. The “buy myself flowers” was a standout. Delicious and creamy. I ended the night with a grasshopper - perfect for a chilly night.

The food was a surprise! I was expecting small bar bites but the mushroom “Forest floor” was filling and so delicious. Three small plates were enough to keep two people happy. Definitely worth coming for a pre-dinner bite or drink!

text.text: We very much adored this place! I love a dark and vampy cocktail bar, which there are many in the city, but this place offers a really refreshing atmosphere which makes it truly unique. Loved the big open space, light and whimsical color choices, and extremely comfortable furniture. I’m a sucker for comfort when socializing with friends, it makes me want to stay longer and spend more money in a establishment. This place really hit the mark on that, and our cocktails were absolutely elegant, fun, and special. I’m a native San Franciscan, and in a lot of ways this reminds me of some of the really cool long gone places that used to be in the city. I went with my girlfriend, and can’t wait to visit again with my hubby. We are in walking distance, yay!

text.text: A great experience at this newish Italian restaurant near the Embarcadero. Stunning interior design greets the eyes as you walk in via the plaza level. Has an old school, proper vibe to the place yet fresh with the mix of modern and retro design features. The staff was all over us ensuring we were cared for and each one offered more than the basics like insight on a drink or menu item. The food was fantastic with a nod to Northern Italy. Fresh ingredients that seemed to all come straight from the farmer’s market. While they were happy to modify most of the dishes to be vegetarian, they do need to focus on adding more vegetarian options that are on the menu. With more intention will bring more wow factor.
